// Nightshift Config interface — declarations of agents, skills, and
// connectors, plus the per-user resolver Workers call at run start.
//
// Config is a domain service layered on Storage. Three resource types
// live here:
//
//   * Agents. Per-user sub-agent definitions (name, description,
//     prompt, allowed tools, model). Passed programmatically to the
//     agent SDK at run start.
//   * Skills. Per-user skill definitions (name, description, SKILL.md
//     content). Hydrated to the worker's filesystem at run start so
//     the agent SDK can discover them.
//   * Connectors. Admin-managed registry of MCP servers with two auth
//     paths — an OAuth code flow whose per-user tokens are minted on
//     demand, and a static bearer token paste-in flow for MCP servers
//     that don't implement OAuth. MCP transport (SSE vs streamable
//     HTTP) is derived from the connector URL; see `config.md` §7.
//
// All three are persisted as Storage Records. Credentials (OAuth
// tokens, static bearer tokens) are NOT stored here — they flow
// through the Secrets interface defined in chunk 5. Config references
// a user's credential by convention; it never holds the bytes.
//
// The Config Dispenser is a single RPC (`GetUserConfig`) that
// materializes a user's effective runtime configuration: their agents,
// their skills, and the MCP server configs for every connector the
// user has successfully authorized. Workers call it once at run start.
//
// Application-level RBAC:
//
//   * Connector writes (`CreateConnector`, `DeleteConnector`) are
//     admin-only — a connector is shared organizational state and
//     mistakes ripple across every user.
//   * Agent, skill, and user-connector-token writes are personal
//     resources. Implementations gate writes on ownership (the caller
//     must match the resource's `user_id`).

